00:55:44.880 --> 00:55:45.560
But

00:55:45.560 --> 00:55:47.500
that's a bit of a pallet cleanser, because

00:55:47.500 --> 00:55:49.400
the whinging is only beginning.

00:55:49.750 --> 00:55:51.030
Now it's time for

00:55:52.300 --> 00:55:54.060
MUSITUDE!

00:55:54.060 --> 00:55:55.410
It’s music,

00:55:55.410 --> 00:55:56.160
but with...

00:55:56.800 --> 00:55:57.250
AAAAAAAAAA

00:55:57.250 --> 00:55:59.410
"Musitude is a music tech startup."

00:55:59.410 --> 00:56:01.420
"Um, here’s a bit of a-
a pie chart for you."

00:56:01.420 --> 00:56:03.590
"So only 3% of people can proficiently"

00:56:03.590 --> 00:56:04.990
"read music and play an instrument."

00:56:05.600 --> 00:56:08.160
"They found that 90% of
non-musicians really want to."

00:56:08.160 --> 00:56:09.320
They really want to?

00:56:09.320 --> 00:56:11.490
Wow, he’s identified a
serious market here.

00:56:11.490 --> 00:56:13.270
90% of all people.

00:56:13.270 --> 00:56:14.670
"So here’s- here's the problem they have."

00:56:14.670 --> 00:56:15.640
"They have to learn"

00:56:15.640 --> 00:56:17.150
"an unfamiliar instrument"

00:56:17.150 --> 00:56:18.770
"AND a complex language."

00:56:18.770 --> 00:56:20.210
"It’s almost like being dyslexic"

00:56:20.210 --> 00:56:21.840
"for a non-musician looking at this."

00:56:21.840 --> 00:56:23.470
Now, before we go any further,

00:56:23.470 --> 00:56:25.730
is his portrayal of the problem accurate?

00:56:25.730 --> 00:56:26.470
Well, let’s see.

00:56:26.470 --> 00:56:28.250
In nearly every Big Massive Whinge

00:56:28.250 --> 00:56:30.020
(or BMW) that I encounter,

00:56:30.020 --> 00:56:31.560
the central whinge is always that

00:56:31.560 --> 00:56:34.480
notation itself is the reason
why beginners give up.

00:56:34.480 --> 00:56:37.920
Now, the stats on people who give up
trying to learn an instrument after a year

00:56:37.920 --> 00:56:38.840
are really high.

00:56:38.840 --> 00:56:40.980
It’s a well known problem
that I discuss constantly

00:56:40.980 --> 00:56:42.740
with peers in other music companies.

00:56:43.020 --> 00:56:44.690
With Ultimate Guitar,
we’re specifically trying to

00:56:44.690 --> 00:56:46.450
find ways to engage more beginners.

00:56:46.450 --> 00:56:47.660
And what we’re finding—

00:56:47.660 --> 00:56:49.500
and what everyone else is finding too—

00:56:49.500 --> 00:56:51.740
is that needing to learn how
to read guitar tablature

00:56:51.740 --> 00:56:53.640
is not the problem beginners are facing.

00:56:53.960 --> 00:56:55.930
Their problem is way more fundamental.

00:56:55.930 --> 00:56:58.850
It’s hard to get a note to ring out
when you press your finger on a string.

00:56:58.850 --> 00:57:01.150
It’s really hard to learn how
to switch between chords.

00:57:01.150 --> 00:57:02.720
It’s hard to pluck the right strings.

00:57:02.720 --> 00:57:04.540
A lot of people get highly frustrated

00:57:04.540 --> 00:57:05.980
trying to learn how to tune a guitar.

00:57:06.290 --> 00:57:07.830
Wind instruments always squawk.

00:57:07.830 --> 00:57:08.910
Violins scratch, and

00:57:08.910 --> 00:57:10.670
it’s hard to get the
pitches to sound right.

00:57:10.670 --> 00:57:13.620
The basic physical realities of
most instruments are tough,

00:57:13.620 --> 00:57:16.340
and there’s not much magic to be
had in the first couple of days

00:57:16.340 --> 00:57:19.030
unless you have, like, a really
good teacher who can guide you.

00:57:19.030 --> 00:57:21.200
Basically, once you’re
able to play a little bit

00:57:21.200 --> 00:57:23.297
by reading simple chords above lyrics,

00:57:23.299 --> 00:57:25.200
you’ve already passed the great filter.

00:57:25.200 --> 00:57:27.510
So when a disruptor emerges to suggest

00:57:27.510 --> 00:57:29.728
that notation is the
reason beginners give up,

00:57:29.730 --> 00:57:30.890
they’re either misinformed

00:57:30.890 --> 00:57:32.680
or just intentionally duplicitous.

00:57:32.680 --> 00:57:34.960
The vast majority are not
starting with notation.

00:57:35.150 --> 00:57:36.960
So, back to the Musitude presentation—

00:57:36.960 --> 00:57:38.780
he’s identified the market opportunity—

00:57:38.780 --> 00:57:40.280
90% of all people.

00:57:40.280 --> 00:57:42.540
Now we need the classic disruptor insight,

00:57:42.540 --> 00:57:44.860
a hidden truth that makes
us sit up in our seats.

00:57:44.860 --> 00:57:47.130
"What’s interesting about
most instruments is..."

00:57:47.130 --> 00:57:48.878
"you’re really using an interface."

00:57:48.880 --> 00:57:51.250
Ah, you’re really using an interface.

00:57:51.250 --> 00:57:52.420
Hmm. Okay, I’m with you.

00:57:52.670 --> 00:57:54.840
"We recognize that there's an interface"

00:57:54.840 --> 00:57:56.810
"a lot of people already know and use."

00:57:56.810 --> 00:57:57.800
"They’re already halfway there."

00:57:57.800 --> 00:57:59.470
"They can play the interface."

00:57:59.470 --> 00:58:01.370
"Of course, they still
can’t read sheet music,"

00:58:01.370 --> 00:58:03.920
"so we invented a new kind of
sheet music to go along with it."

00:58:03.920 --> 00:58:05.550
So, this is his proposal…

00:58:05.750 --> 00:58:07.508
QWERTY keyboard tablature.

00:58:07.650 --> 00:58:10.040
"So, these are some comparative shots."

00:58:10.040 --> 00:58:12.020
"This is a Beethoven sonata,
the melody part."

00:58:12.300 --> 00:58:13.740
But hold on. Even in this example,

00:58:13.740 --> 00:58:15.190
the system doesn’t hold up, so...

00:58:15.190 --> 00:58:16.460
Right. If we look here—

00:58:16.460 --> 00:58:18.390
that’s this bar in the notation view—

00:58:18.390 --> 00:58:20.320
we can see that this
note is held for 2 beats

00:58:20.320 --> 00:58:22.420
and this note is held for 2 beats.

00:58:22.420 --> 00:58:23.200
That’s fine.

00:58:23.200 --> 00:58:25.460
So the connected circles
are 2 beats long. Got it.

00:58:25.810 --> 00:58:27.450
Now, if we look at this bar, we can see

00:58:27.450 --> 00:58:29.770
that a single circle represents 1 beat.

00:58:29.770 --> 00:58:30.300
So:

00:58:30.300 --> 00:58:32.070
dum, dum, dum, dum.

00:58:32.070 --> 00:58:32.710
Fine.

00:58:33.050 --> 00:58:34.100
But then if you look here,

00:58:34.690 --> 00:58:35.890
this note isn’t 1 beat.

00:58:35.890 --> 00:58:37.710
In the notation, it’s 1 and a half beats

00:58:37.710 --> 00:58:39.630
because it uses the prick of perfection.

00:58:39.630 --> 00:58:41.900
And these notes are twice
as long as they should be.

00:58:41.900 --> 00:58:43.410
Your rhythm is completely wrong.

00:58:43.410 --> 00:58:45.100
So even in his presentation,

00:58:45.100 --> 00:58:48.310
this guy has demonstrated a
total disinterest in actual music—

00:58:48.310 --> 00:58:51.968
or his system is just so useless, it can’t
capture basic musical performance.

00:58:51.970 --> 00:58:53.140
But the real fun part is

00:58:53.140 --> 00:58:55.820
how the notes are arranged on the
keyboard and what they're called.

00:58:55.820 --> 00:58:58.560
Okay, so the lowest note
starts on the digit 1

00:58:58.560 --> 00:58:59.880
and then goes up to 5,

00:58:59.880 --> 00:59:02.010
then A, B, C, D, E, F. G,

00:59:02.010 --> 00:59:03.600
then you proceed all the way to Z,

00:59:03.600 --> 00:59:05.750
followed by 6, 7, 8, 9, 0.

00:59:05.750 --> 00:59:07.390
Thereby ending on F#,

00:59:07.390 --> 00:59:09.730
cutting out only a few octaves
of the upper range.

00:59:09.730 --> 00:59:12.210
What do you do?
Hold caps lock to transpose?

00:59:12.210 --> 00:59:14.050
But the whinging is only getting started.

00:59:14.050 --> 00:59:15.050
According to our boy,

00:59:15.050 --> 00:59:17.060
notation is really confusing because of

00:59:17.060 --> 00:59:19.610
how the notes are named
A to G in a given octave,

00:59:19.610 --> 00:59:22.160
and then restart again
on A in the next octave.

00:59:22.700 --> 00:59:25.700
"And then you go 'A, B, C, D, E, F, G'
and then it’ll go ‘A’ again."

00:59:25.700 --> 00:59:27.950
"And- And then they use the same names"

00:59:27.950 --> 00:59:29.980
"for the next level or
set of notes above it"

00:59:29.980 --> 00:59:32.090
"and then the same name
again and then again."

00:59:32.470 --> 00:59:34.370
"It can get confusing if someone says,"

00:59:35.070 --> 00:59:36.220
"‘that’s the letter G’."

00:59:36.220 --> 00:59:37.720
I agree it would be confusing

00:59:37.720 --> 00:59:40.050
in any context if another musician
turned to you and said,

00:59:40.050 --> 00:59:41.528
"That’s the letter G".

00:59:41.530 --> 00:59:43.830
Leave your comments below
proposing musical scenarios

00:59:43.830 --> 00:59:45.840
where it would actually be
appropriate for someone to say,

00:59:45.840 --> 00:59:47.210
‘That’s the letter G’!

00:59:47.210 --> 00:59:48.670
The moment you start thinking about this,

00:59:48.670 --> 00:59:49.730
the funnier it gets.

00:59:50.020 --> 00:59:52.160
So the system, as championed by Musitude,

00:59:52.160 --> 00:59:55.250
requires that notes an octave apart
should all have different names.

00:59:55.250 --> 00:59:56.640
You need to remember that 1

00:59:56.640 --> 00:59:59.170
is the same pitch as but
an octave lower than H,

00:59:59.170 --> 01:00:01.390
which in turn is an octave lower than T,

01:00:01.390 --> 01:00:03.300
and then you’ll have to learn
that each of the other pitches

01:00:03.300 --> 01:00:05.040
also has 3 variations.

01:00:05.770 --> 01:00:07.080
What I really love about this system

01:00:07.080 --> 01:00:10.010
isn’t just that it ignores how
we commonly name notes.

01:00:10.010 --> 01:00:12.950
It's that intentionally hostile
to how we name notes.

01:00:12.950 --> 01:00:15.760
For example, 'H' in Musitude
is what we call 'G'.

01:00:15.760 --> 01:00:18.060
'A' on Musitude is what we call 'C'.

01:00:18.060 --> 01:00:20.970
So, if you're collaborating with a
musician unfamiliar with this system,

01:00:20.970 --> 01:00:22.990
you’d need to convert it
backwards, remembering that

01:00:22.990 --> 01:00:23.940
'3' is 'A',

01:00:23.940 --> 01:00:24.610
'J' is 'A',

01:00:24.610 --> 01:00:25.990
and 'V' is also 'A',

01:00:25.990 --> 01:00:27.990
making a total nuisance of yourself.

01:00:27.990 --> 01:00:30.400
And this is why Musitude
is my favourite disrupter.

01:00:30.400 --> 01:00:33.830
Because it’s intentionally incompatible
with every instrument in existence,

01:00:33.830 --> 01:00:35.390
and can only be played on a device

01:00:35.390 --> 01:00:37.850
not intended to be used
for musical performance.

01:00:37.850 --> 01:00:40.100
It has to be the most revolutionary
system I’ve ever seen

01:00:40.100 --> 01:00:42.260
in that basically nothing
can exist as it is.

01:00:42.260 --> 01:00:43.280
Everything must burn—

01:00:43.280 --> 01:00:44.570
including all music theory—

01:00:44.570 --> 01:00:46.070
so that we can all sit at our keyboards

01:00:46.070 --> 01:00:48.480
🎵
awkwardly hammering out ditties like this:

01:00:48.480 --> 01:00:53.450
🎵

01:00:53.820 --> 01:00:54.640
So, in summary,

01:00:54.640 --> 01:00:57.210
the solution for that 90% who
want to play an instrument

01:00:57.210 --> 01:00:59.860
is that they should learn something
that isn’t a musical instrument.

01:00:59.860 --> 01:01:00.730
Amazing.

01:01:00.990 --> 01:01:02.380
And also, just look at this.

01:01:02.700 --> 01:01:03.930
'The Joy Barrier'?

01:01:04.340 --> 01:01:07.080
Oh, having to learn
things is a joy barrier!

01:01:07.080 --> 01:01:09.800
I for one object to the barriers for joy.

01:01:09.800 --> 01:01:12.070
Jesus, can someone
give this man a lollipop?

01:01:12.070 --> 01:01:14.220
Along with one of those
hats with a spinner on it.

01:01:14.220 --> 01:01:15.490
If you want instant joy,

01:01:15.490 --> 01:01:16.540
go to a carnival!

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:18.220
Or take ecstacy!

01:01:18.720 --> 01:01:20.190
But if you think that whinging is bad—

01:01:20.190 --> 01:01:22.250
and I’m gonna have to issue
a whinge warning here,

01:01:22.250 --> 01:01:23.630
let me introduce you to

01:01:23.630 --> 01:01:24.500
Dodeka.

01:01:25.960 --> 01:01:27.100
“For me, it’s not logical.”

01:01:27.360 --> 01:01:28.390
“I couldn’t play.”

01:01:29.100 --> 01:01:30.970
“I always had problems with keys.”

01:01:31.320 --> 01:01:32.420
“I had to stop.”

01:01:32.860 --> 01:01:33.520
Well, you know,

01:01:33.520 --> 01:01:34.660
maybe I’m being a bit harsh.

01:01:34.660 --> 01:01:37.280
Like, it’s easy to talk about
these things in the abstract,

01:01:37.280 --> 01:01:39.760
but when you’re confronted
by testimonials like this,

01:01:39.760 --> 01:01:41.530
it’s hard to ignore what they’re saying.

01:01:42.440 --> 01:01:43.190
Unless...

01:01:43.580 --> 01:01:46.780
Unless these people are literally
the founders of Dodeca saying it.

01:01:46.780 --> 01:01:48.100
"This complexity"

01:01:48.100 --> 01:01:50.710
"leads to the loss of many
potential musicians."

01:01:50.710 --> 01:01:52.010
So yes, Moody Fonze

01:01:52.010 --> 01:01:53.460
and Professor Wheeto here

01:01:53.460 --> 01:01:55.400
are the masterminds behind this system.

01:01:55.400 --> 01:01:58.340
Here’s Professor Wheeto having a
good old whinge about notation.

01:01:58.340 --> 01:01:59.000
Oh look!

01:01:59.000 --> 01:02:00.580
He’s holding a ball of tangled-up string

01:02:00.580 --> 01:02:02.030
and an image of a maze.

01:02:02.030 --> 01:02:02.840
I get it!

01:02:03.070 --> 01:02:04.960
And you’ll never guess
what their solution is?

01:02:04.960 --> 01:02:06.500
It’s a chromatic staff!

01:02:06.500 --> 01:02:07.900
This time, there are 4 lines

01:02:07.900 --> 01:02:10.540
(not including the extra 3 you
should imagine in your mind)

01:02:10.540 --> 01:02:13.600
as well as the numerous invisible
lines that exist between staves.

01:02:13.830 --> 01:02:15.780
And again, durations are relative.

01:02:15.780 --> 01:02:18.320
I’m beginning to think the main
beneficiaries of this video are

01:02:18.320 --> 01:02:20.280
the potential reformers of the future.

01:02:20.280 --> 01:02:23.320
Before you go and propose
for the 2000th time

01:02:23.320 --> 01:02:25.620
a chromatic staff with relative durations,

01:02:25.620 --> 01:02:28.320
just take a look at some of the
proposals already in existence

01:02:28.320 --> 01:02:30.110
and champion one of those instead!

01:02:30.400 --> 01:02:31.190
To be fair though,

01:02:31.190 --> 01:02:34.670
Dodeca do actually try to consider
more modern developments in music—

01:02:34.670 --> 01:02:36.460
namely microtonality—

01:02:36.460 --> 01:02:39.420
although their solution is to
use very subtle slanted angles

01:02:39.420 --> 01:02:41.080
to mean different kinds of microtone,

01:02:41.080 --> 01:02:42.820
which I find a little bit weak.

01:02:42.820 --> 01:02:46.308
But it already puts them five or six
musical levels above Musitude.

01:02:46.310 --> 01:02:49.460
Although, on the metric of pure,
unadulterated whinging,

01:02:49.460 --> 01:02:50.500
they stand alone:

01:02:50.500 --> 01:02:51.730
“Reading music?"

01:02:51.730 --> 01:02:52.680
"Me?”

01:02:52.680 --> 01:02:53.250
“No."

01:02:53.250 --> 01:02:54.620
"That was just impossible”

01:02:54.620 --> 01:02:56.780
“I thought I was stupid, but in fact"

01:02:56.780 --> 01:02:58.600
"the system is quite stupid.”

01:03:09.170 --> 01:03:11.700
For me, the aspect of notation
that I find most troubling

01:03:11.700 --> 01:03:13.320
relates to accessibility.

01:03:13.320 --> 01:03:15.490
I've not been able to
locate statistics on this,

01:03:15.490 --> 01:03:17.500
so I’ll have to rely
anecdotally on problems

01:03:17.500 --> 01:03:20.250
described to me from users
and friends over the years.

01:03:20.700 --> 01:03:22.300
Some people have trouble reading notation

01:03:22.300 --> 01:03:25.220
due to different kinds of visual
or perceptual impairment.

01:03:25.530 --> 01:03:27.670
Some readers complain of
a kind of phasing effect

01:03:27.670 --> 01:03:29.700
when trying to focus on
the lines between notes,

01:03:29.700 --> 01:03:31.630
which makes them very tricky to read,

01:03:31.630 --> 01:03:32.920
sometimes causing headaches.

01:03:33.320 --> 01:03:36.570
Some report a difficulty in
distinguishing lines from spaces.

01:03:36.570 --> 01:03:38.770
I have heard numerous
times from dyslexic readers

01:03:38.770 --> 01:03:40.850
that the tightly packed nature of notation

01:03:40.850 --> 01:03:42.140
makes it hard to parse.

01:03:42.140 --> 01:03:44.350
Vertical arrangement can become confused.

01:03:44.350 --> 01:03:46.990
Certain combinations of notes
become visually muddled.

01:03:46.990 --> 01:03:48.850
For blind users, thankfully,

01:03:48.850 --> 01:03:51.500
Louis Braille—the inventor
whose namesake became

01:03:51.500 --> 01:03:54.860
the universally recognised system
that allows blind people to read text—

01:03:54.860 --> 01:03:56.790
was also an experienced musician.

01:03:56.790 --> 01:03:58.280
Along with regular braille,

01:03:58.280 --> 01:04:00.460
he also devised a system of music braille,

01:04:00.460 --> 01:04:02.480
although it isn’t as
supported as it should be

01:04:02.480 --> 01:04:05.660
and requires better integration with
notation apps and screen readers.

01:04:05.990 --> 01:04:07.630
For those suffering from dyslexia,

01:04:07.630 --> 01:04:10.430
there are a few known approaches
that can improve legibility,

01:04:10.430 --> 01:04:12.260
such as using note names with noteheads,

01:04:12.260 --> 01:04:13.550
altering the staff size

01:04:13.550 --> 01:04:16.430
and using colours to help reinforce
which notes are to be played.

01:04:16.430 --> 01:04:19.340
The only trouble is that most
publicly available sheet music

01:04:19.340 --> 01:04:21.880
does not come with these
kinds of accessible variations.

01:04:21.880 --> 01:04:24.540
I’ll come back to accessibility
at the end of this video.

01:04:24.540 --> 01:04:26.180
But for now, all I’ll say is that

01:04:26.180 --> 01:04:28.490
the trouble with trying to
find an accessible standard,

01:04:28.490 --> 01:04:31.410
is that a solution for one reader
can be a barrier to another.

01:04:31.410 --> 01:04:32.340
In particular,

01:04:32.340 --> 01:04:35.050
care is needed when suggesting
approaches that use colour,

01:04:35.050 --> 01:04:37.950
since colour blindness is another
common accessibility problem.

01:04:37.950 --> 01:04:39.650
And that takes me quite neatly

01:04:39.650 --> 01:04:43.000
to what is probably the most incredible
proposal featured in this video:

01:04:47.160 --> 01:04:48.100
<i>Farbige Noten</i>.

01:04:48.540 --> 01:04:50.610
This is a proposal from
a different reality.

01:04:50.610 --> 01:04:52.710
Amazingly strange and impractical

01:04:52.710 --> 01:04:55.830
but proposed in the most
incredibly visually beautiful way,

01:04:55.830 --> 01:04:59.390
and I’m over the moon that I managed
to track down the original publication,

01:04:59.390 --> 01:05:01.618
because you have to see
how this looks in print.

01:05:01.620 --> 01:05:02.560
<i>Farbige Noten</i>,

01:05:02.560 --> 01:05:03.860
or ‘coloured notes’

01:05:03.860 --> 01:05:05.580
was published in 1888

01:05:05.580 --> 01:05:06.660
by Christian Huth.

01:05:06.660 --> 01:05:09.910
It starts with a lengthy treatise on the
relationship between colours and pitch,

01:05:09.910 --> 01:05:12.860
culminating in a proposal that
each of the 12 notes of the scale

01:05:12.860 --> 01:05:14.830
should have their own unique colour.

01:05:14.830 --> 01:05:15.910
But that’s not all.

01:05:15.910 --> 01:05:18.120
Huth goes into much more specific detail,

01:05:18.120 --> 01:05:20.510
proposing for example
that the key of C major is

01:05:20.510 --> 01:05:23.560
9 parts blue, 8 parts orange
and 7 parts yellow.

01:05:23.560 --> 01:05:27.560
C minor is 7 parts green,
6 parts orange and 5 parts blue.

01:05:27.560 --> 01:05:29.870
The notation itself is
represented as a grid.

01:05:29.870 --> 01:05:31.990
Like many of the other proposals
we’ve already looked at,

01:05:31.990 --> 01:05:33.100
durations are relative—

01:05:33.100 --> 01:05:35.190
with durations represented
by these curves.

01:05:35.190 --> 01:05:37.370
And since the grid is
pretty tight horizontally,

01:05:37.370 --> 01:05:39.790
smaller durations get
really physically cramped.

01:05:40.870 --> 01:05:42.920
The numbers here are
meant to represent octaves,

01:05:42.920 --> 01:05:45.510
which makes sense because
pitch is represented by colour

01:05:45.510 --> 01:05:47.360
so it doesn’t need to be
represented vertically.

01:05:47.360 --> 01:05:49.210
However, it gets pretty mind-bending

01:05:49.210 --> 01:05:50.570
because, for some reason,

01:05:50.570 --> 01:05:52.700
vertical placement can
sometimes be ignored

01:05:52.700 --> 01:05:54.530
and the same note can
jump around vertically

01:05:54.530 --> 01:05:58.250
according to a logic I don’t quite
trust myself to adequately explain.

01:05:58.250 --> 01:06:01.290
I think this means that
<i>Farbige Noten</i> is the only proposal

01:06:01.290 --> 01:06:04.460
which doesn’t fit into either of the
two fundamental types of notation

01:06:04.460 --> 01:06:06.170
identified by Geavert.

01:06:06.170 --> 01:06:07.100
Now, rhythmically,

01:06:07.100 --> 01:06:09.640
this proposal matches a bunch
of the others we’ve looked at.

01:06:09.640 --> 01:06:11.480
However, the question of
whether we’d be able to

01:06:11.480 --> 01:06:13.450
sight-read numerous colours
at the same time

01:06:13.450 --> 01:06:15.400
and be able to interpret them reliably

01:06:15.400 --> 01:06:17.910
is one it’s safe to say
I’m sceptical about.

01:06:17.910 --> 01:06:20.350
We tend to use colour as
an aid to other symbols

01:06:20.350 --> 01:06:22.530
but rarely as the primary symbol itself.

01:06:22.530 --> 01:06:25.630
Gardner Read’s assessment of
this proposal is pretty amusing:

01:06:25.630 --> 01:06:28.640
“This notation is so far removed
from standard practice,"

01:06:28.640 --> 01:06:30.590
"so idiosyncratic in symbology,"

01:06:30.590 --> 01:06:32.850
"and so elaborately
fanciful in construction"

01:06:32.850 --> 01:06:35.580
"that it defies professionally
objective assessment."

01:06:35.580 --> 01:06:39.180
"The analyst may be awed by the
detail and extent of Huth’s schema,"

01:06:39.180 --> 01:06:42.010
"but mystified by his
Jovian disregard of reality."

01:06:42.010 --> 01:06:42.770
And, by the way,

01:06:42.770 --> 01:06:45.500
I’ve a lot to say about the relationship
between colour and sound

01:06:45.500 --> 01:06:46.830
because, for one thing,

01:06:46.830 --> 01:06:49.040
it was the subject of
my old master's thesis.

01:06:49.040 --> 01:06:50.800
There’ll be a video about it one day.

01:06:52.070 --> 01:06:53.360
For maximum whiplash,

01:06:53.360 --> 01:06:55.520
let’s now look at what is—for my money—

01:06:55.520 --> 01:06:57.540
probably the most logical and convincing

01:06:57.540 --> 01:06:59.890
outright replacement
reform I think I’ve seen.

01:07:00.170 --> 01:07:02.050
It was proposed by Julian Carrillo—

01:07:02.050 --> 01:07:04.160
an influential microtonal composer—

01:07:04.160 --> 01:07:05.460
in 1895.

01:07:05.730 --> 01:07:07.490
First, the 12 pitches of the octave

01:07:07.490 --> 01:07:09.030
are represented by numbers.

01:07:09.030 --> 01:07:11.320
Middle-range pitches are
placed on the central line.

01:07:11.320 --> 01:07:12.920
If they’re displayed on a lower space,

01:07:12.920 --> 01:07:14.040
they’re an octave lower.

01:07:14.040 --> 01:07:15.010
Another space down,

01:07:15.010 --> 01:07:16.410
an octave lower again.

01:07:16.410 --> 01:07:18.560
A space up, an octave higher. et cetera.

01:07:18.860 --> 01:07:19.680
And that’s it.

01:07:19.680 --> 01:07:22.020
No need for flat or
sharp symbols or clefs—

01:07:22.020 --> 01:07:23.580
and it’s way more vertically efficient—

01:07:23.580 --> 01:07:26.030
as can be seen by comparing
this notated example

01:07:26.030 --> 01:07:27.780
with Carrillo’s proposed system.

01:07:28.200 --> 01:07:29.750
For sure, it would mean
that we’d have to recalibrate

01:07:29.750 --> 01:07:31.340
our relationship to music theory.

01:07:31.340 --> 01:07:32.820
For example, you’d need to learn that

01:07:32.820 --> 01:07:34.950
2, 6, 9 is a D major chord.

01:07:34.950 --> 01:07:37.310
2, 5, 9 is a D minor chord, et cetera.

01:07:37.310 --> 01:07:38.800
It messes with our heads now,

01:07:38.800 --> 01:07:40.120
but it’s completely sensible,

01:07:40.120 --> 01:07:42.880
and the numeric relationship
would always be consistent.

01:07:43.120 --> 01:07:45.540
Another reason Carrillo
created this system

01:07:45.540 --> 01:07:47.720
was so that it could accommodate
different tuning systems

01:07:47.720 --> 01:07:49.390
and microtonality too.

01:07:49.680 --> 01:07:52.300
For example, using 24-tone
equal temperament,

01:07:52.300 --> 01:07:55.240
or you could represent quarter
tones with decimals or fractions,

01:07:55.240 --> 01:07:56.130
et cetera.

01:07:56.130 --> 01:07:58.030
The two probable downsides I can see

01:07:58.030 --> 01:08:00.390
are difficulties in understanding
what key you are in

01:08:00.390 --> 01:08:02.200
or what key you are modulating to.

01:08:02.200 --> 01:08:04.980
But if I was to pick out the issue
that might cause the most trouble,

01:08:04.980 --> 01:08:07.290
my guess is it would be
how chords are visualised—

01:08:07.290 --> 01:08:08.920
I just don’t know how easy it would be

01:08:08.920 --> 01:08:11.140
for a performer to chunk
these numbers quickly,

01:08:11.140 --> 01:08:14.060
although I should mention that there are
some types of non-Western notation

01:08:14.060 --> 01:08:15.590
that use numbers in this way.

01:08:16.090 --> 01:08:18.660
We’d really need some serious
comparative data to judge

01:08:18.660 --> 01:08:20.580
how successful Carrillo’s system could be

01:08:20.580 --> 01:08:22.060
compared to standard notation.

01:08:22.060 --> 01:08:23.560
But even if it didn’t compare well,

01:08:23.560 --> 01:08:25.400
it’s an honourable attempt for sure.

01:08:34.090 --> 01:08:35.940
Now, as much as I’d love
to spend another hour

01:08:35.940 --> 01:08:37.570
going through a ton of other systems,

01:08:37.570 --> 01:08:38.910
I do fear for your brain.

01:08:38.910 --> 01:08:42.400
So I thought I’d just cycle through a
couple of other proposed reforms quickly

01:08:42.400 --> 01:08:44.520
before tying everything
up in my conclusion.

01:08:45.370 --> 01:08:46.300
Hummingbird.

01:08:46.300 --> 01:08:48.210
This one is a relatively recent proposal,

01:08:48.210 --> 01:08:50.140
and I find it quite baffling.

01:08:50.140 --> 01:08:52.600
These weird balls have
shading that indicates pitch—

01:08:52.600 --> 01:08:55.810
even though they’re still represented
vertically a-la standard notation.

01:08:55.810 --> 01:08:58.470
It’s like the authors couldn’t choose
between one idea over the other

01:08:58.470 --> 01:08:59.730
so just used both.

01:08:59.730 --> 01:09:02.060
The squiggly bits
represent sharps or flats.

01:09:02.060 --> 01:09:03.220
Durations have a little line

01:09:03.220 --> 01:09:05.160
which is meant to tell
you how long they last.

01:09:05.160 --> 01:09:07.990
These extra adjacent lines indicate 8ths.

01:09:07.990 --> 01:09:09.710
I think it’s a total nightmare to look at.

01:09:09.710 --> 01:09:11.850
Perhaps at very early
stages it might be useful,

01:09:11.850 --> 01:09:14.950
but it seems too messy and
indistinct for anything beyond that.

01:09:15.750 --> 01:09:17.110
Stenographic notation

01:09:17.110 --> 01:09:19.030
(or notation shorthand).

01:09:19.030 --> 01:09:20.960
This is not one proposal in particular,

01:09:20.960 --> 01:09:22.340
it’s an entire genre.

01:09:22.340 --> 01:09:24.700
I’m not showing these here because
I think they need to be assessed.

01:09:24.700 --> 01:09:25.930
I just think they’re fun.

01:09:25.930 --> 01:09:27.960
In 1802, John Austin proposed

01:09:27.960 --> 01:09:29.470
these symbols for pitch

01:09:29.470 --> 01:09:31.320
and these symbols for duration,

01:09:31.880 --> 01:09:33.330
which would alter this notation

01:09:33.330 --> 01:09:34.440
to look like this.

01:09:35.140 --> 01:09:37.530
Another from Harry White in 1899

01:09:37.530 --> 01:09:39.270
would represent this notation,

01:09:39.270 --> 01:09:40.340
like this.

01:09:40.340 --> 01:09:41.410
And my favourite,

01:09:41.410 --> 01:09:42.730
in 1873,

01:09:42.730 --> 01:09:44.320
Alex M. Seymat proposed

01:09:44.320 --> 01:09:46.630
the use of these symbols
to represent pitch,

01:09:46.630 --> 01:09:47.960
which means this notation

01:09:47.960 --> 01:09:49.150
would look like this.

01:09:50.590 --> 01:09:53.890
'Global Notation' is a recent
proposal by Dr. Andrew Killick

01:09:53.890 --> 01:09:56.600
from the Department of Music
at the University of Sheffield.

01:09:56.600 --> 01:09:58.430
Its purpose is to provide, quote,

01:09:58.430 --> 01:10:01.610
“...a more realistic picture of
what listeners actually hear”,

01:10:01.610 --> 01:10:03.320
by using a complex grid to represent

01:10:03.320 --> 01:10:04.930
pitch, pitch variation,

01:10:04.930 --> 01:10:06.310
note events, and time.

01:10:06.310 --> 01:10:07.680
Pitch is represented by cents,

01:10:07.680 --> 01:10:10.180
and duration is—again—relative.

01:10:10.640 --> 01:10:12.330
By being this technical and literal,

01:10:12.330 --> 01:10:15.010
it aims to be able to notate
music from all cultures.

01:10:15.010 --> 01:10:17.700
It was initially proposed as
a new way to write music,

01:10:17.700 --> 01:10:20.970
accompanied by the boilerplate
notation whinge you come to expect.

01:10:21.210 --> 01:10:22.910
However, from a performer’s point of view,

01:10:22.910 --> 01:10:26.540
it is far less legible than many similar
proposals we’ve already looked at.

01:10:26.540 --> 01:10:28.430
One particularly awkward thing about it

01:10:28.430 --> 01:10:31.760
is how the staff lines change
depending on the pitch ranges used,

01:10:31.760 --> 01:10:33.980
which means the performer
can never rely on memory

01:10:33.980 --> 01:10:36.770
to know what these lines
mean in any given piece.

01:10:36.770 --> 01:10:39.510
So they’d have to constantly reference
the cent numbers on the left

01:10:39.510 --> 01:10:41.470
to know what pitch
they’re supposed to play.

01:10:41.470 --> 01:10:43.780
Also, there’s a weirdness
in its basic premise.

01:10:43.780 --> 01:10:46.710
If it’s supposed to represent
what the listener actually hears,

01:10:46.710 --> 01:10:48.660
then the performance must
have already happened,

01:10:48.660 --> 01:10:52.140
so it seems to me to be more of an
aid to an existing audio recording

01:10:52.140 --> 01:10:54.920
rather than an instruction on
how to perform in the first place.

01:10:55.190 --> 01:10:57.410
The goals of Global Notation
have narrowed since.

01:10:57.410 --> 01:10:58.680
As of 2021,

01:10:58.680 --> 01:11:00.660
its stated purpose is purely academic—

01:11:00.660 --> 01:11:03.390
a tool to be used in the analysis
of non-Western music.

01:11:03.700 --> 01:11:06.820
Certainly, there are many cases
where standard notation is insufficient—

01:11:06.820 --> 01:11:08.860
like in describing micro-variant textures

01:11:08.860 --> 01:11:10.960
found in Carnatic music, for example.

01:11:10.960 --> 01:11:13.810
So Global Notation is certainly
a sensible proposal.

01:11:13.810 --> 01:11:17.060
Whether it will be successful as a
system used in ethnomusicology

01:11:17.060 --> 01:11:18.310
remains to be seen.

01:11:19.020 --> 01:11:20.900
Jianpu is a straightforward system

01:11:20.900 --> 01:11:23.720
used successfully in
early-stage learning in China.

01:11:23.720 --> 01:11:26.400
It’s essentially a variation of
the tonic sol-fa system,

01:11:26.400 --> 01:11:28.590
where Do, Re, Mi, Fa, Sol, La, Ti

01:11:28.590 --> 01:11:29.860
are replaced by numbers.

01:11:29.860 --> 01:11:31.460
Dots are placed above or below

01:11:31.460 --> 01:11:34.190
to indicate whether the octave
should be higher or lower.

01:11:34.190 --> 01:11:36.790
Although it superficially looks
similar to Carrillo’s system,

01:11:36.790 --> 01:11:38.040
it is completely different.

01:11:38.040 --> 01:11:39.430
More suitable for basic music,

01:11:39.430 --> 01:11:41.790
with obvious limitations
once you go beyond that.

01:11:41.790 --> 01:11:43.590
However, it’s really popular in China,

01:11:43.590 --> 01:11:45.360
so worthy of a deeper investigation

01:11:45.360 --> 01:11:46.890
as a potential early aide.

01:11:54.650 --> 01:11:56.380
So, after all of this investigating—

01:11:56.380 --> 01:11:58.090
what conclusions can we come to?

01:11:58.090 --> 01:11:59.490
Well, before I get to that,

01:11:59.490 --> 01:12:01.430
I just want to talk about
