01:12:53.020 --> 01:12:54.770
Since it’s clear that I
haven’t found a system

01:12:54.770 --> 01:12:56.860
I believe should replace
standard notation,

01:12:56.860 --> 01:12:59.890
do we really have to just accept
that things should never change?

01:13:00.270 --> 01:13:01.270
Well, no.

01:13:01.270 --> 01:13:02.430
As we’ve seen earlier,

01:13:02.430 --> 01:13:04.950
the development of notation
happened very slowly

01:13:04.950 --> 01:13:06.550
for around 600 years,

01:13:06.550 --> 01:13:08.700
but it didn’t stop 2 or 3 centuries ago.

01:13:08.700 --> 01:13:10.820
Various changes still slowly happen,

01:13:10.820 --> 01:13:12.550
with older, more ornate systems

01:13:12.550 --> 01:13:14.280
gradually becoming simplified.

01:13:14.280 --> 01:13:15.750
Now, in the 20th century,

01:13:15.750 --> 01:13:18.490
there was an explosion of
adapted notation systems,

01:13:18.490 --> 01:13:20.900
created to accommodate
different types of music.

01:13:20.900 --> 01:13:22.170
Microtonal music,

01:13:22.170 --> 01:13:25.380
free-metered music, and aleatoric
music particularly stand out.

01:13:25.380 --> 01:13:29.140
I created a video about aleatoricism
a few years ago, if you’re interested.

01:13:29.140 --> 01:13:31.470
There are also all kinds
of bespoke scores—

01:13:31.470 --> 01:13:34.050
like those created by
Karlheinz Stockhausen,

01:13:34.050 --> 01:13:36.090
which combined elements
of standard notation

01:13:36.090 --> 01:13:38.090
with different types of
graphic visualisation

01:13:38.090 --> 01:13:40.270
to achieve specific musical effects.

01:13:40.710 --> 01:13:42.890
In these scores, you can
often spot many ideas

01:13:42.890 --> 01:13:45.590
from some of the proposals
we've looked at in this video.

01:13:45.590 --> 01:13:48.270
There are also many kinds
of abstract notation too,

01:13:48.270 --> 01:13:50.840
which introduce varying
degrees of ambiguity

01:13:50.840 --> 01:13:53.250
to prompt novel types
of musical performance.

01:13:53.250 --> 01:13:55.490
Some scores are works of
art in their own right.

01:13:55.490 --> 01:13:58.130
However, the move to digital
around the 80s and 90s

01:13:58.130 --> 01:13:59.690
was slow and clunky—

01:13:59.690 --> 01:14:01.230
and I also feel it contributed to

01:14:01.230 --> 01:14:03.470
halting some of these
20th-century developments,

01:14:03.470 --> 01:14:04.980
since digital applications

01:14:04.980 --> 01:14:07.400
simply couldn’t accommodate
much experimentation.

01:14:07.400 --> 01:14:09.070
This is true even today.

01:14:09.070 --> 01:14:11.130
However, digital apps will catch up,

01:14:11.130 --> 01:14:13.020
broadening the possibilities
for what you can do

01:14:13.020 --> 01:14:14.500
by just being more flexible.

01:14:14.960 --> 01:14:16.180
And related to this point,

01:14:16.180 --> 01:14:17.840
let me jump into MuseScore to show you

01:14:17.840 --> 01:14:19.610
some of the things it can currently do.

01:14:19.610 --> 01:14:21.930
Here, I’m looking at a
standard notation view.

01:14:21.930 --> 01:14:23.380
But if I make one little change.

01:14:23.380 --> 01:14:26.250
The same data is now
displayed as guitar tab instead.

01:14:26.250 --> 01:14:28.350
I can also switch it to coloured notation.

01:14:28.350 --> 01:14:30.340
I can switch it to solfege noteheads.

01:14:30.340 --> 01:14:31.490
Just a few months ago,

01:14:31.490 --> 01:14:33.710
we released a version that
works with Braille readers,

01:14:33.710 --> 01:14:36.860
and we’re currently developing
the ability to display Jianpu.

01:14:36.860 --> 01:14:38.890
The data is the same
for all these formats,

01:14:38.890 --> 01:14:40.580
so switching between them is easy.

01:14:40.580 --> 01:14:42.560
So what’s needed now is further expansion

01:14:42.560 --> 01:14:45.230
to accommodate more
systems and more flexibility.

01:14:45.230 --> 01:14:47.400
And this is where I think the
change needs to happen:

01:14:47.400 --> 01:14:49.820
we need to move to a
completely digital format.

01:14:49.820 --> 01:14:51.770
A format which, unlike PDF,

01:14:51.770 --> 01:14:54.220
retains and understands musical data.

01:14:54.220 --> 01:14:55.290
When that happens,

01:14:55.290 --> 01:14:57.260
musicians can choose
whatever format they want.

01:14:57.260 --> 01:14:58.540
Chromatic staves,

01:14:58.540 --> 01:15:00.150
systems with relative durations,

01:15:00.150 --> 01:15:01.280
coloured notation,

01:15:01.280 --> 01:15:02.180
a piano roll,

01:15:02.180 --> 01:15:03.220
Klavarskribo,

01:15:03.220 --> 01:15:03.810
Jianpu.

01:15:03.810 --> 01:15:04.960
The list goes on.

01:15:04.960 --> 01:15:06.730
The next logical step beyond that

01:15:06.730 --> 01:15:10.280
would see this format applied to
digitised theory textbooks too.

01:15:10.540 --> 01:15:13.650
This would weaken the need to
agree on one unchanging system.

01:15:13.650 --> 01:15:16.100
And the price of introducing
changes would be much lower

01:15:16.100 --> 01:15:19.550
because digital textbooks wouldn’t need
to be rewritten to accommodate them.

01:15:19.550 --> 01:15:21.200
You’d just add the latest standard.

01:15:21.710 --> 01:15:23.060
Now, all that aside,

01:15:23.060 --> 01:15:24.880
if you are not a person
who reads notation,

01:15:24.880 --> 01:15:26.880
I hope I’ve successfully demonstrated

01:15:26.880 --> 01:15:28.120
that it is not something dead,

01:15:28.120 --> 01:15:29.860
which belongs to a bygone era.

01:15:29.860 --> 01:15:33.050
It’s a living, breathing system
that belongs to us, now.

01:15:33.050 --> 01:15:35.410
It’s also frankly nowhere
near as hard to learn

01:15:35.410 --> 01:15:36.670
as some would have you believe,

01:15:36.670 --> 01:15:39.230
and learning it has
enormously benefited my life.

01:15:39.470 --> 01:15:41.410
Despite its flaws and compromises,

01:15:41.410 --> 01:15:44.330
standard notation is a
remarkable cultural achievement,

01:15:44.330 --> 01:15:45.930
universal for all instruments

01:15:45.930 --> 01:15:48.250
and which transcends
spoken language barriers.

01:15:48.480 --> 01:15:49.450
A system that—

01:15:49.450 --> 01:15:52.730
just like the mediaeval chess game
we saw at the beginning of this video—

01:15:52.730 --> 01:15:54.670
allows us to reach into the past

01:15:54.670 --> 01:15:56.730
to understand the ideas of our ancestors.

01:15:56.730 --> 01:15:59.530
A direct link to our history
that’s incredibly valuable

01:15:59.530 --> 01:16:00.900
and worth preserving.

01:16:01.180 --> 01:16:03.700
Notation will continue to
change over the centuries

01:16:03.700 --> 01:16:04.890
and, for my money,

01:16:04.890 --> 01:16:07.110
won’t be dying any time soon.

